\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Molecular Dynamics Study of Anisotropic Lattice Diffusion in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
P.
 Cao, D.
 M.
 Wells, M.
 P.
 Short
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Charge-corrected molecular dynamics (MD) studies of anion and cation self-diffus
ion, as well as cation dopant diffusion, have been performed using nudged
 elastic band (NEB) analysis on 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Non-negligible anisotropy in the diffusion coefficients between a- and
 c-axes, increasing in magnitude with decreasing temperature, was observed
 for all species studied (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr^{3+},\, O^{2-},\, Fe^{3+},\, Ni^{2+}}$
\end_inset

).
 Trends in relative diffusivities, as well as absolute orders of magnitude,
 agree well with multiple experimental measurements.
 Because of the ubiquitous technological importance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 as the most frequently used corrosion-protecting passivation layer, especially
 on stainless steel, any method of reducing transport through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 has profound implications for the reduction and control of corrosion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chromium oxide 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 is arguably the world's most important oxide.
 It functions as the primary passivating protective layer of the world's
 most utilized corrosion-resistant structural material, stainless steel.
 Currently the production of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

-passivated stainless steels continues to grow expotentially, reaching 41.7
 million metric tons in 2014 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "(ISSF)2015"

\end_inset

, underpinning critical infrastructures ranging from bridges, to buildings,
 to nuclear reactors.
 The continued corrosion-based upkeep cost of stainless steel alone reaching
 $___billion pear year worldwide [REF - get from Ballinger].
 Therefore, any deterministic ways of slowing the progress of oxygen penetration
 from the environment into the metal, or conversely of metal escape from
 the metal into the environment, however small, would constitute a substantial
 reduction in the total costs of corrosion worldwide.
 Even a 10% reduction in corrosion rate could save $___billion per year,
 in addition to increasing inspection intervals and decreasing failure rates
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

-passivated components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One well-known method of controlling corrosion rates governed by ionic transport
 is to control the texture or anisotropy of the material.
 This has been well-characterized in stainless steels, where the corrosion
 rates of both 304 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RaviKumar2005"

\end_inset

 and 316 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shahryari2009"

\end_inset

 were found to directly vary with local crystallographic orientation, separately
 from the effects of stress-induced 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

-martensite.
 While the substrate orientation was cited as the determining factor, it
 is almost certainly the character of the passive 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 layer which controls the corrosion rate.
 The character of the oxide layer, including its orientation, is itself
 almost certainly determined by the orientation of the underlying substrate.
 These studies point to the texture of the underlying steel changing the
 character of the oxide layer on top.
 This effect has been observed in other passivating materials as well.
 Kudelka et al showed how differently oriented grains of Ti corrode at different
 rates, by studying oxide texture and thicknesses on individual grains in
 the same experiment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kudelka1995"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, Hoseini et al showed varying rates of corrosion by impedance
 spectroscopy to vary with grain orientation in annealed and severly plasticly
 deformed (SPD) titanium, attributing the change in corrosion rate specifically
 to substrate grain orientation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hoseini2009"

\end_inset

.
 Even oxidation of pure platinum exhibits a clear dependence on the underlying
 metal orientation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Conway1992"

\end_inset

.
 Clearly the effect of underlying metal orientation changes the nature of
 the passivating, corrosion-resistant oxide layer on top.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For passivating materials which function as effective diffusion barriers
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jones1996"

\end_inset

, the difference between directionally-different diffusivities will determine
 the relative, texture-dependent corrosion rates through these materials.
 Examples of anisotropic cation and anion diffusion through non-cubic oxides
 exist throughout the literature.
 These will be reivewed briefly here, with emphasis on those that explore
 the diffusion mechanisms, not just the rates, behind cation and anion transport.
 Chroneos et al showed preferential oxygen diffusion in the 
\emph on
a-b
\emph default
 plane of tetragonal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{La_{2}NiO_{4+\delta}}$
\end_inset

 using MD simulations which explained formerly anomalous experimental measuremen
ts which varied by a factor of up to 4.5 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chroneos2010"

\end_inset

.
 Kendrick et al showed the importance of mechanistic understanding in predicting
 the diffusivity of oxygen through Ga-based oxides, with their results agreeing
 well with experiments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kendrick2007"

\end_inset

.
 The critical importance of understanding diffusion mechanisms through anisotrop
ic oxides in the form of solid oxide fuel cells was recently highlighted
 by Chroneos et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chroneos2011"

\end_inset

, underscoring the need for more than the standard experiments/simulations
 showing simply gross rates of transport without explanation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dopants can also change oxygen penetration through oxides, either by substition
 or by ordering.
 Parfitt et al showed that cation disorder changes oxygen anion diffusion
 anisotropy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parfitt2011"

\end_inset

, showing how cation ordering can affect anion transport through oxides.
 [MORE TO COME ON DOPING SOON]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transport of cations and anions specifically through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 has been experimentally and theoretically studied, though to a degree far
 lower than would be expected given its technological importance.
 The experimental literature is more extensive, as tracer experiments of
 oxygen and cation transport have been quantified by multiple groups.
 Hagel experimentally found that anion diffusion is slower through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 compared to cation diffusion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hagel1965"

\end_inset

.
 Sabioni et al.
 studied the diffusion of oxygen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sabioni1992"

\end_inset

, manganese 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sabioni2005"

\end_inset

, chromium 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sabioni2012"

\end_inset

, and iron 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sabioni2007"

\end_inset

 through chromia polycrystals and thin films by secondary ion mass spectroscopy
 (SIMS), eventually finding that oxygen diffusivity is faster than that
 of chromium in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

.
 Lobnig et al also used tracer experiments to study the diffusion of Cr,
 Fe, and Ni through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lobnig1992"

\end_inset

 as functions of time, while Tsai et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tsai1996"

\end_inset

 and Hoshino et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hoshino1983"

\end_inset

 experimentally studied the mechanisms of diffusion of Cr and O through
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, Hoshino et al specifically studied 
\emph on
a-
\emph default
 vs.
 
\emph on
c-
\emph default
axis oxygen anion diffusion, and found 
\emph on
c-
\emph default
axis diffusion to be faster 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hoshino1983"

\end_inset

.
 The literature concerning simulations of ionic transport 
\emph on
through
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 are surprisingly scarce, though studies of surface structure are more common.
 Catlow et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Catlow1988"

\end_inset

 and Vaari 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vaari2015"

\end_inset

 have predicted diffusion coefficients of cations and anions through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 with comparisons to experimental values, showing mixed results.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 has a hexagonal close-packed (HCP) crystal structure with a 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{c}{a}$
\end_inset

 axis ratio of 2.74 over a very wide pressure range 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Finger1980"

\end_inset

, any application utilizing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 as a passivation layer, from near-vacuum to ultra-high pressure, should
 benefit from the same texture-based gains in transport resistance.
 Therefore, precise knowledge of the orientation-dependent transport rates
 determines whether this strategy can succeed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this manuscript, we present detailed, mechanism-based molecular dynamics
 simulations of oxygen and cation (Fe, Ni, Cr) diffusion through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

.
 A combination of defect formation energies, nudged elastic band (NEB) analysis,
 and extrapolation to lower temperatures via defect population scaling is
 shown to yield diffusion coefficients similar to those in the experimental
 results above.
 Most interesting is a clear anisotropy observed for both oxygen and cations,
 which increases at lower temperatures, pointing to the potentially enhanced
 corrosion resistance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 at ___ orientations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The LAMMPS MD code 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Plimpton1995"

\end_inset

 was used in all simulations in this study.
 The diffusion coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Fe^{3+},\, Cr^{3+},\, Ni^{3+},\, and\, O^{2-}}$
\end_inset

 were all studied in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 directly at temperatures ranging from 1200-2000K.
 The effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Fe^{3+}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ni^{2+}}$
\end_inset

 cation dopant concentrations on the diffusion rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O^{2-}}$
\end_inset

 up to concentrations of 0.15 atom fraction was also quantified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interactions between self-ions, dopant ions, and combinations thereof
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 were modeled by combining a short range Buckingham potential and a longer
 range Coulombic potential.
 The Buckingham potential is specifically chosen for its ability to model
 short-range charged defect interactions [REFs], as well as maintaining
 overall charge neurality of the MD simulation.
 The Coulombic potential models charge attraction/repulsion effects between
 ions, at distances greater than the atomic radii.
 The potential for the interaction between two ions 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
j
\emph default
 at a distance 
\emph on
r
\emph default
 is defined by Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Buckingham-Potential"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{ij}\left(r\right)=A_{ij}e^{\nicefrac{-r}{\rho_{ij}}}-\frac{C_{ij}}{r_{ij}}+\frac{q_{i}q_{j}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}r_{ij}}\label{eq:Buckingham-Potential}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the parameters 
\emph on
A
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, and 
\emph on
C
\emph default
 are taken from the previous studies of Grimes et al and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Grimes1995,Minervini2000"

\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Buckingham-Coulomb-Pairs"

\end_inset

 lists the parameters and references used for the various ions in this study.
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

