\begin_layout Standard
Like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\alpha-Al_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Fe_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\alpha-Cr_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 has the corundum structure.
 [ADD UNIT CELL DESCRIPTION].
 Simulations were carried out using a 18×18×18 hexagonal supercell containing
 58,320 atoms as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Unit-Cell-Schematic"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Unit-Cell-Schematic"

\end_inset

Schematic of unit cell used in the simulations in this study
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

 Periodic boundary conditions were used in all three directions.
 To study vacancy- and interstitial-assisted ion diffusion, ions were randomly
 inserted or deleted in the system.
 In these simulations, vacancy and interstital defects were studied at concentra
tions of 0.0008 at different temperatures, with low-temperature extrapolation
 performed by adjusting diffusion coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(D\right)$
\end_inset

 for lower numbers of thermally stable vacancies following Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Diffusion-Coefficient-Simple"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\left(T\right)=\alpha a^{2}C\left(T\right)\omega=\alpha a^{2}C\left(T\right)f_{Debye}e^{\nicefrac{-E_{m}}{k_{B}T}}\label{eq:Diffusion-Coefficient-Simple}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the successful jump frequency of an ion from one site to another, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{f_{Debye}}$
\end_inset

 is the jump attempt frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{E_{m}}$
\end_inset

 is the defect migration energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{k_{B}}$
\end_inset

 is Boltzmann's constant, 
\emph on
T
\emph default
 is the system temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a crystallographic constant relating the jump distance to the lattice
 parameter, 
\emph on
a
\emph default
 is the lattice parameter, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(T\right)$
\end_inset

 is the thermally stable population of a particular defect.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(T\right)$
\end_inset

 can be defined by Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Equilibrium-Defect-Concentration"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C=e^{\nicefrac{-E_{f}}{k_{B}T}}\label{eq:Equilibrium-Defect-Concentration}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{E_{f}}$
\end_inset

 is the defect formation energy.
 The above diffusivity equation can therefore be written by Equation :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\left(T\right)=\alpha a^{2}f_{Debye}e^{\nicefrac{-\left(E_{f}+E_{m}\right)}{k_{B}T}}\label{eq:Diffusion-Coefficient}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before the diffusion coefficient calculation, the system is relaxted at
 zero pressure for 100 ps in the NPT (constant number of atoms, pressure
 and temperature) and another 100 ps run is performed in the NVT ensemble
 (constant number of atoms, volume and temperature).
 The Nose-Hoover thermostat is used in time intergration and the time step
 is set to be 1 fs.
 The ion diffusion was determinated measureing mean square displacement
 (MSD) of ions as a function of time at a range of temperatures.
 The MSD of ion is described by Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MSD"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \Delta r^{2}\left(t\right)\right\rangle =\frac{1}{N}\underset{i=1}{\overset{n}{\sum}}\left[r_{i}\left(t+t_{0}\right)-r_{i}\left(t_{0}\right)\right]^{2}\label{eq:MSD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where N is total number of the ion in the system, r(t 0 ) is initial reference
 position at time t 0 and r(t) is position at time t + t 0 .
 The diffusivity that relates MSD to the observe time t is defined in Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Diffusion-Coefficient-Formula"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\frac{\left\langle r^{2}\left(t\right)\right\rangle }{2d\times t}\label{eq:Diffusion-Coefficient-Formula}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\emph on
d
\emph default
 is dimensionality of the system.
 Then, the diffusivities of ions along the c-axis, in the ab-plane and in
 three dimensions can be calculated by Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:c-Diffusion"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3D-Diffusion"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
D_{c} & = & \frac{\left\langle r_{c}^{2}\left(t\right)\right\rangle }{2t}\label{eq:c-Diffusion}\\
D_{ab} & = & \frac{\left\langle r_{ab}^{2}\left(t\right)\right\rangle }{4t}\label{eq:ab-Diffusion}\\
D_{3D} & = & \frac{\left\langle r_{abc}^{2}\left(t\right)\right\rangle }{6t}\label{eq:3D-Diffusion}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Each diffusion coefficient was calculated by fitting the MSD as a function
 of time (see Supplementary Material S_ for an example).
 All diffusion simuations were performed in NVT emsamble by extensive simulation
 time of 1
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

ns to ensure adequate statistical sampling.
 Migration energy barriers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(E_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

 for each ion travelling along potential diffusion paths were found by NEB
 analysis.
 [PENGHUI, PLEASE EXPLAIN THE NEB PROCESS HERE].
 An example of how this process was applied to the simulations in this manuscrip
t is shown in Supplementary Material S_.
 Finally, calculated diffusion coefficients were extrapolated to lower temperatu
res, by scaling the values found using Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:c-Diffusion"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3D-Diffusion"

\end_inset

 by the difference in 
\end_layout

